Author: Akrem

Pickup classes:
The pickup classes are organized pretty well around a shared BasePickup, which keeps common behavior like position, hitbox, drawing, and collision structure in one place. The main improvement I would suggest is reducing some duplicated pickup logic between ConsumablePickup, InventoryPickup, and ShopPickup, since they all handle assigning the item entity, applying effects, and discontinuing the pickup in slightly different ways.

Item interfaces and base item classes:
The item interface structure is clear and makes it easy to distinguish between consumable, inventory, passive, and active items. The marker interfaces are simple and useful, but some classes blur categories a bit, like active items also implementing IInventoryItem, so it may help to document exactly what each item type means in the inventory system.

Passive and consumable items:
The passive and consumable items are easy to follow, and each item mostly has one clear responsibility. A small issue is that some values are hardcoded, like sound names, stat multipliers, and effect durations, so moving those into constants or data files would make balancing and future changes easier.

Active items:
The active item classes do a good job separating temporary effects from permanent passive effects, especially with timers and cooldown logic. However, there is some repeated timer/cooldown code between AdrenalineItem, InvincibilityItem, and TeleportItem, so a shared helper method or base cooldown behavior in ActiveItem would improve maintainability.

PickupFactory and PickupManager:
PickupFactory is useful because it centralizes item and pickup creation instead of spreading that logic throughout the room code. The main downside is that item creation is currently based on string matching, so adding new items requires editing the factory directly, which could become harder to maintain as the item list grows.

ShopPickup:
ShopPickup is a strong extension of the regular pickup system because it adds price logic without needing a completely separate system. One thing to watch is that purchasing, applying effects, adding inventory items, and drawing price text are all handled in this one class, so it may become too large if shop behavior gets more complex.

Sound classes:
The sound system has a solid basic structure with SoundFactory loading sounds and SoundManager controlling playback. The singleton approach makes it easy to access sounds globally, but it also creates tighter coupling, so future testing or replacement of the sound system may be harder.

Overall:
Overall, these classes show good use of interfaces, inheritance, and object-oriented organization. The biggest improvements would be reducing repeated effect/cooldown logic, avoiding hardcoded strings and magic numbers, and making item creation more data-driven so new items can be added with fewer code changes.
